Jean Ponsot

Only last week, we took a bottle of Ponsot’s Clos de la Roche 1966 from our cellars and tasted it. In the com- pany of objective wine authorities, the universal verdict was ‘‘one of the greatest red Burgundies we have ever tasted, regardless of price.” And M. Ponsot claims his 1969 is even better! Our advice is to acquire a few bottles of the 1966 while we still have them—judge it—and if you agree, reserve a case of his 1969. Jean Ponsot, unlike most of his neighbors, sticks to old-fashioned methods and simply refuses to de- stem when vinifying his wines—the result is that they are big, deep tannic, slow-maturing and excep- tionally long-lived. This is not only true for Clos de la Roche, but also for his other vineyard holdings in Chambolle-Musigny and Chamber- tin.
